item.contentencoded:
If you've wondered what Prion Alliance's logo represents, it's the direction of progress, which as everyone knows is up and to the right. More specifically, think of it as an abstract representation of this graph which we hold to be a quick overview of our species' past, present and future:

<a href="http://www.prionalliance.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/prion-alliance-the-future.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-228" title="our view of human history" src="http://www.prionalliance.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/prion-alliance-the-future.png" alt="" width="212" height="204" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

In fact, it's not entirely clear whether prions can even be passed by blood transfusion, though the answer is probably "yes, but rarely". A review of potential transfusion cases in Britain found just 3 cases in which it looked like prions had probably been transmitted by blood transfusion [<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16958834">Hewitt 2006</a>]. All 3 suspect transfusions were from donors infected with variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (vCJD), which is the human form of mad cow disease or bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE). Another case was reported later which was almost certainly linked to transfusion from a vCJD blood donor, though the recipient had only a prion infection of the spleen, which had never reached his brain to cause disease [<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20070383">Peden 2010</a>].

So far there's no evidence that vCJD (or any other prion disease) can be transmitted from parent to child [<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19401289">Murray 2011</a>], or that health care workers exposed to prion disease patients have been infected [<a href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22516047">Alcalde-Cabero 2012</a>].

It's important to note that because vCJD is acquired from the diet, prions are present first in the peripheral tissues (including blood) and only later in the brain. That's different from sporadic or genetic prion diseases which, as far as we know, probably start in the brain.

